{"parse":{"title":"Discussion moderator","pageid":41994398,"revid":856108048,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><div class=\"thumb tright\"><div class=\"thumbinner\" style=\"width:222px;\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:CNBC_World_Economic_Forum_debate.jpg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/85/CNBC_World_Economic_Forum_debate.jpg/220px-CNBC_World_Economic_Forum_debate.jpg\" width=\"220\" height=\"141\" class=\"thumbimage\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/85/CNBC_World_Economic_Forum_debate.jpg/330px-CNBC_World_Economic_Forum_debate.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/85/CNBC_World_Economic_Forum_debate.jpg/440px-CNBC_World_Economic_Forum_debate.jpg 2x\" data-file-width=\"4054\" data-file-height=\"2605\" /></a>  <div class=\"thumbcaption\"><div class=\"magnify\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:CNBC_World_Economic_Forum_debate.jpg\" class=\"internal\" title=\"Enlarge\"></a></div><a href=\"/wiki/Geoff_Cutmore\" title=\"Geoff Cutmore\">Geoff Cutmore</a>, standing, moderates a debate on economic policy between James S. Turley and Ruben K. Vardanian.</div></div></div>\n<div class=\"thumb tright\"><div class=\"thumbinner\" style=\"width:222px;\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Kennedy_Nixon_Debat_(1960).jpg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/50/Kennedy_Nixon_Debat_%281960%29.jpg/220px-Kennedy_Nixon_Debat_%281960%29.jpg\" width=\"220\" height=\"149\" class=\"thumbimage\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/50/Kennedy_Nixon_Debat_%281960%29.jpg/330px-Kennedy_Nixon_Debat_%281960%29.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/50/Kennedy_Nixon_Debat_%281960%29.jpg/440px-Kennedy_Nixon_Debat_%281960%29.jpg 2x\" data-file-width=\"1194\" data-file-height=\"810\" /></a>  <div class=\"thumbcaption\"><div class=\"magnify\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Kennedy_Nixon_Debat_(1960).jpg\" class=\"internal\" title=\"Enlarge\"></a></div>A 1960 <a href=\"/wiki/United_States_presidential_debate\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"United States presidential debate\">United States presidential debate</a> between <a href=\"/wiki/John_F._Kennedy\" title=\"John F. Kennedy\">John F. Kennedy</a> and <a href=\"/wiki/Richard_Nixon\" title=\"Richard Nixon\">Richard Nixon</a> had a panel of four moderators.</div></div></div>\n<p>A <b>discussion moderator</b> or <b>debate moderator</b> is a person whose role is to act as a neutral participant in a debate or discussion, holds participants to time limits and tries to keep them from straying off the topic of the questions being raised in the debate.  Sometimes moderators may ask questions intended to allow the debate participants to fully develop their argument in order to ensure the debate moves at pace.\n</p><p>In panel discussions commonly held at <a href=\"/wiki/Academic_conference\" title=\"Academic conference\">academic conferences</a>, the moderator usually introduces the participants and solicits questions from the audience. On television and radio shows, a moderator will often take calls from people having differing views, and will use those calls as a starting point to ask questions of guests on the show. Perhaps the most prominent role of moderators is in <a href=\"/wiki/Political_debate\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Political debate\">political debates</a>, which have become a common feature of election campaigns. The moderator may have complete control over which questions to ask, or may act as a filter by selecting questions from the audience.\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"History\">History</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Discussion_moderator&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: History\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>The role of the discussion moderator became significant in the year 1780, when a \"Rage for publick debate\" led to a number of different organizations advertising and hosting debates for anywhere between 650 and 1200 people.<sup id=\"cite_ref-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> The question for debate was introduced by a president or moderator who proceeded to regulate the discussion. Speakers were given set amounts of time to argue their point of view, and, at the end of the debate, a vote was taken to determine a decision or adjourn the question for further debate.<sup id=\"cite_ref-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup> Speakers were not permitted to slander or insult other speakers, or diverge from the topic at hand, illustrating the value placed on politeness.<sup id=\"cite_ref-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>In the <a href=\"/wiki/Television\" title=\"Television\">television</a> era, it is common for political debate moderators to be <a href=\"/wiki/Journalism\" title=\"Journalism\">journalists</a>, either individually or as a panel.<sup id=\"cite_ref-4\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-4\">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Discussion_moderator&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"reflist\" style=\"list-style-type: decimal;\">\n<div class=\"mw-references-wrap\"><ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-1\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Donna T. Andrew, Introduction to <i>London Debating Societies,</i> ix; Mary Thale, \"London Debating Societies in the 1790s,\" <i>The Historical Journal</i> 32, no. 1 (March 1989), p. 59.; Thomas Munck, <i>The Enlightenment: A Comparative Social History 1721-1794</i> (New York: Oxford University Press, 2000), p. 72.</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-2\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-2\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Thale, \"London Debating Societies in the 1790s,\" 60.</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-3\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-3\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Andrew, \"Popular Culture and Public Debate,\" 409.</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-4\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-4\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Laura Robinson, Shelia R. Cotton, Jeremy Schulz, <i>Communication and Information Technologies Annual</i> (2015), p. 36.</span>\n</li>\n</ol></div></div>\n\n<!-- \nNewPP limit report\nParsed by mw2237\nCached time: 20180914154900\nCache expiry: 1900800\nDynamic content: false\nCPU time usage: 0.036 seconds\nReal time usage: 0.051 seconds\nPreprocessor visited node count: 115/1000000\nPreprocessor generated node count: 0/1500000\nPost\u2010expand include size: 344/2097152 bytes\nTemplate argument size: 84/2097152 bytes\nHighest expansion depth: 7/40\nExpensive parser function count: 0/500\nUnstrip recursion depth: 0/20\nUnstrip post\u2010expand size: 1483/5000000 bytes\nNumber of Wikibase entities loaded: 0/400\nLua time usage: 0.005/10.000 seconds\nLua memory usage: 525 KB/50 MB\n-->\n<!--\nTransclusion expansion time report (%,ms,calls,template)\n100.00%   29.362      1 Template:Reflist\n100.00%   29.362      1 -total\n  7.64%    2.242      1 Template:Main_other\n-->\n\n<!-- Saved in parser cache with key enwiki:pcache:idhash:41994398-0!canonical and timestamp 20180914154900 and revision id 856108048\n -->\n</div>"},"langlinks":[{"lang":"bg","url":"https://bg.wikipedia.org/wiki/%D0%9C%D0%BE%D0%B4%D0%B5%D1%80%D0%B0%D1%82%D0%BE%D1%80","langname":"Bulgarian","autonym":"\u0431\u044a\u043b\u0433\u0430\u0440\u0441\u043a\u0438","*":"\u041c\u043e\u0434\